# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: workflow-orchestration
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In mathematics, particularly graph theory, and computer science, a **directed acyclic graph** (**DAG**) is a directed graph with no directed cycles.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] That is, it consists of vertices and edges (also called *arcs*), with each edge directed from one vertex to another, such that following those directions will never form a closed loop.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed graph is a DAG if and only if it can be topologically ordered, by arranging the vertices as a linear ordering that is consistent with all edge directions.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] DAGs have numerous scientific and computational applications, ranging from biology (evolution, family trees, epidemiology) to information science (citation networks) to computation (scheduling).
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graphs are also called **acyclic directed graphs** or **acyclic digraphs**.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A graph is formed by vertices and by edges connecting pairs of vertices, where the vertices can be any kind of object that is connected in pairs by edges.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In the case of a directed graph, each edge has an orientation, from one vertex to another vertex.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A walk in a directed graph is a (finite or infinite) sequence $(v_{1},v_{2},\dotsc )$ of vertices such that each consecutive pair $(v_{i},v_{i+1})$ is connected by a directed edge.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A path is a walk where all vertices are distinct.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A cycle is a walk $(v_{1},v_{2},\dotsc ,v_{n})$ where the only repeated vertex is $v_{n}=v_{1}$ , meaning the last vertex equals the first vertex.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic graph is a directed graph that has no cycles.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The reachability relation of a DAG can be formalized as a partial order ≤ on the vertices of the DAG.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In this partial order, two vertices u and v are ordered as *u* ≤ *v* exactly when there exists a directed path from u to v in the DAG; that is, when u can reach v (or v is reachable from u).
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] However, different DAGs may give rise to the same reachability relation and the same partial order.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, a DAG with two edges *u* → *v* and *v* → *w* has the same reachability relation as the DAG with three edges *u* → *v*, *v* → *w*, and *u* → *w*.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Both of these DAGs produce the same partial order, in which the vertices are ordered as *u* ≤ *v* ≤ *w*.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive closure of a DAG is the graph with the most edges that has the same reachability relation as the DAG.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] It has an edge *u* → *v* for every pair of vertices (u, v) in the reachability relation ≤ of the DAG, and may therefore be thought of as a direct translation of the reachability relation ≤ into graph-theoretic terms.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In this way, every finite partially ordered set can be represented as a DAG.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive reduction of a DAG is the graph with the fewest edges that has the same reachability relation as the DAG.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] It has an edge *u* → *v* for every pair of vertices (u, v) in the covering relation of the reachability relation ≤ of the DAG.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] It is a subgraph of the DAG, formed by discarding the edges *u* → *v* for which the DAG also contains a longer directed path from u to v.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Like the transitive closure, the transitive reduction is uniquely defined for DAGs.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In contrast, for a directed graph that is not acyclic, there can be more than one minimal subgraph with the same reachability relation.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Transitive reductions are useful in visualizing the partial orders they represent, because they have fewer edges than other graphs representing the same orders and therefore lead to simpler graph drawings.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A Hasse diagram of a partial order is a drawing of the transitive reduction in which the orientation of every edge is shown by placing the starting vertex of the edge in a lower position than its ending vertex.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] goes from earlier in the ordering (upper left) to later in the ordering (lower right).
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed graph is acyclic if and only if it has a topological ordering.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A topological ordering of a directed graph is an ordering of its vertices into a sequence, such that for every edge the start vertex of the edge occurs earlier in the sequence than the ending vertex of the edge.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A graph that has a topological ordering cannot have any cycles, because the edge into the earliest vertex of a cycle would have to be oriented the wrong way.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Therefore, every graph with a topological ordering is acyclic.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Conversely, every directed acyclic graph has at least one topological ordering.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The existence of a topological ordering can therefore be used as an equivalent definition of a directed acyclic graphs: they are exactly the graphs that have topological orderings.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In general, this ordering is not unique; a DAG has a unique topological ordering if and only if it has a directed path containing all the vertices, in which case the ordering is the same as the order in which the vertices appear in the path.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The family of topological orderings of a DAG is the same as the family of linear extensions of the reachability relation for the DAG, so any two graphs representing the same partial order have the same set of topological orders.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The graph enumeration problem of counting directed acyclic graphs was studied by Robinson (1973).
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] (2004) proved, that the same numbers count the (0,1) matrices for which all eigenvalues are positive real numbers.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The proof is bijective: a matrix A is an adjacency matrix of a DAG if and only if *A* + *I* is a (0,1) matrix with all eigenvalues positive, where I denotes the identity matrix.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Because a DAG cannot have self-loops, its adjacency matrix must have a zero diagonal, so adding I preserves the property that all matrix coefficients are 0 or 1.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A *multitree* (also called a *strongly unambiguous graph* or a *mangrove*) is a DAG in which there is at most one directed path between any two vertices.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Equivalently, it is a DAG in which the subgraph reachable from any vertex induces an undirected tree.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A *polytree* (also called a *directed tree*) is a multitree formed by orienting the edges of an undirected tree.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] An *arborescence* is a polytree formed by orienting the edges of an undirected tree away from a particular vertex, called the *root* of the arborescence.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Topological sorting is the algorithmic problem of finding a topological ordering of a given DAG.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Kahn's algorithm for topological sorting builds the vertex ordering directly.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] It maintains a list of vertices that have no incoming edges from other vertices that have not already been included in the partially constructed topological ordering; initially this list consists of the vertices with no incoming edges at all.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Then, it repeatedly adds one vertex from this list to the end of the partially constructed topological ordering, and checks whether its neighbors should be added to the list.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The algorithm terminates when all vertices have been processed in this way.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Alternatively, a topological ordering may be constructed by reversing a postorder numbering of a depth-first search graph traversal.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Any undirected graph may be made into a DAG by choosing a total order for its vertices and directing every edge from the earlier endpoint in the order to the later endpoint.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The resulting orientation of the edges is called an acyclic orientation.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Different total orders may lead to the same acyclic orientation, so an n-vertex graph can have fewer than *n*! acyclic orientations.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The number of acyclic orientations is equal to |*χ*(−1)|, where χ is the chromatic polynomial of the given graph.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Any directed graph may be made into a DAG by removing a feedback vertex set or a feedback arc set, a set of vertices or edges (respectively) that touches all cycles.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] However, the smallest such set is NP-hard to find.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] An arbitrary directed graph may also be transformed into a DAG, called its condensation, by contracting each of its strongly connected components into a single supervertex.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] When the graph is already acyclic, its smallest feedback vertex sets and feedback arc sets are empty, and its condensation is the graph itself.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive closure of a given DAG, with n vertices and m edges, may be constructed in time *O*(*mn*) by using either breadth-first search or depth-first search to test reachability from each vertex.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Alternatively, it can be solved in time *O*(*n**ω*) where *ω* < 2.373 is the exponent for matrix multiplication algorithms; this is a theoretical improvement over the *O*(*mn*) bound for dense graphs.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In all of these transitive closure algorithms, it is possible to distinguish pairs of vertices that are reachable by at least one path of length two or more from pairs that can only be connected by a length-one path.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive reduction consists of the edges that form length-one paths that are the only paths connecting their endpoints.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Therefore, the transitive reduction can be constructed in the same asymptotic time bounds as the transitive closure.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The closure problem takes as input a vertex-weighted directed acyclic graph and seeks the minimum (or maximum) weight of a closure – a set of vertices *C*, such that no edges leave *C*.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The problem may be formulated for directed graphs without the assumption of acyclicity, but with no greater generality, because in this case it is equivalent to the same problem on the condensation of the graph.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] It may be solved in polynomial time using a reduction to the maximum flow problem.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Some algorithms become simpler when used on DAGs instead of general graphs, based on the principle of topological ordering.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, it is possible to find shortest paths and longest paths from a given starting vertex in DAGs in linear time by processing the vertices in a topological order, and calculating the path length for each vertex to be the minimum or maximum length obtained via any of its incoming edges.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In contrast, for arbitrary graphs the shortest path may require slower algorithms such as Dijkstra's algorithm or the Bellman–Ford algorithm, and longest paths in arbitrary graphs are NP-hard to find.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graph representations of partial orderings have many applications in scheduling for systems of tasks with ordering constraints.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] An important class of problems of this type concern collections of objects that need to be updated, such as the cells of a spreadsheet after one of the cells has been changed, or the object files of a piece of computer software after its source code has been changed.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In this context, a dependency graph is a graph that has a vertex for each object to be updated, and an edge connecting two objects whenever one of them needs to be updated earlier than the other.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A cycle in this graph is called a circular dependency, and is generally not allowed, because there would be no way to consistently schedule the tasks involved in the cycle.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Dependency graphs without circular dependencies form DAGs.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, when one cell of a spreadsheet changes, it is necessary to recalculate the values of other cells that depend directly or indirectly on the changed cell.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] For this problem, the tasks to be scheduled are the recalculations of the values of individual cells of the spreadsheet.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Dependencies arise when an expression in one cell uses a value from another cell.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In such a case, the value that is used must be recalculated earlier than the expression that uses it.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Topologically ordering the dependency graph, and using this topological order to schedule the cell updates, allows the whole spreadsheet to be updated with only a single evaluation per cell.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Similar problems of task ordering arise in makefiles for program compilation and instruction scheduling for low-level computer program optimization.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A somewhat different DAG-based formulation of scheduling constraints is used by the program evaluation and review technique (PERT), a method for management of large human projects that was one of the first applications of DAGs.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In this method, the vertices of a DAG represent milestones of a project rather than specific tasks to be performed.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Instead, a task or activity is represented by an edge of a DAG, connecting two milestones that mark the beginning and completion of the task.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Each such edge is labeled with an estimate for the amount of time that it will take a team of workers to perform the task.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The longest path in this DAG represents the critical path of the project, the one that controls the total time for the project.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Individual milestones can be scheduled according to the lengths of the longest paths ending at their vertices.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic graph may be used to represent a network of processing elements.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In this representation, data enters a processing element through its incoming edges and leaves the element through its outgoing edges.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, in electronic circuit design, static combinational logic blocks can be represented as an acyclic system of logic gates that computes a function of an input, where the input and output of the function are represented as individual bits.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In general, the output of these blocks cannot be used as the input unless it is captured by a register or state element which maintains its acyclic properties.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Electronic circuit schematics either on paper or in a database are a form of directed acyclic graphs using instances or components to form a directed reference to a lower level component.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Electronic circuits themselves are not necessarily acyclic or directed.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Dataflow programming languages describe systems of operations on data streams, and the connections between the outputs of some operations and the inputs of others.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] These languages can be convenient for describing repetitive data processing tasks, in which the same acyclically-connected collection of operations is applied to many data items.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] They can be executed as a parallel algorithm in which each operation is performed by a parallel process as soon as another set of inputs becomes available to it.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In compilers, straight line code (that is, sequences of statements without loops or conditional branches) may be represented by a DAG describing the inputs and outputs of each of the arithmetic operations performed within the code.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] This representation allows the compiler to perform common subexpression elimination efficiently.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] At a higher level of code organization, the acyclic dependencies principle states that the dependencies between modules or components of a large software system should form a directed acyclic graph.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Feedforward neural networks are another example.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Graphs in which vertices represent events occurring at a definite time, and where the edges always point from an earlier time vertex to a later time vertex, are necessarily directed and acyclic.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The lack of a cycle follows because the time associated with a vertex always increases as you follow any directed path in the graph, so you can never return to a vertex on a path.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] This reflects our natural intuition that causality means events can only affect the future, they never affect the past, and thus we have no causal loops.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] An example of this type of directed acyclic graph are those encountered in the causal set approach to quantum gravity though in this case the graphs considered are transitively complete.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In the version history example below, each version of the software is associated with a unique time, typically the time the version was saved, committed or released.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In the citation graph examples below, the documents are published at one time and can only refer to older documents.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Sometimes events are not associated with a specific physical time.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Provided that pairs of events have a purely causal relationship, that is edges represent causal relations between the events, we will have a directed acyclic graph.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, a Bayesian network represents a system of probabilistic events as vertices in a directed acyclic graph, in which the likelihood of an event may be calculated from the likelihoods of its predecessors in the DAG.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In this context, the moral graph of a DAG is the undirected graph created by adding an (undirected) edge between all parents of the same vertex (sometimes called *marrying*), and then replacing all directed edges by undirected edges.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Another type of graph with a similar causal structure is an influence diagram, the vertices of which represent either decisions to be made or unknown information, and the edges of which represent causal influences from one vertex to another.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In epidemiology, for instance, these diagrams are often used to estimate the expected value of different choices for intervention.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] That is in any application represented by a directed acyclic graph there is a causal structure, either an explicit order or time in the example or an order which can be derived from graph structure.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] This follows because all directed acyclic graphs have a topological ordering, i.e. there is at least one way to put the vertices in an order such that all edges point in the same direction along that order.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Family trees may be seen as directed acyclic graphs, with a vertex for each family member and an edge for each parent-child relationship.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Despite the name, these graphs are not necessarily trees because of the possibility of marriages between relatives (so a child has a common ancestor on both the mother's and father's side) causing pedigree collapse.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The graphs of matrilineal descent (mother-daughter relationships) and patrilineal descent (father-son relationships) are trees within this graph.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Because no one can become their own ancestor, family trees are acyclic.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The version history of a distributed revision control system, such as Git, generally has the structure of a directed acyclic graph, in which there is a vertex for each revision and an edge connecting pairs of revisions that were directly derived from each other.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] These are not trees in general due to merges.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In many randomized algorithms in computational geometry, the algorithm maintains a *history DAG* representing the version history of a geometric structure over the course of a sequence of changes to the structure.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance in a randomized incremental algorithm for Delaunay triangulation, the triangulation changes by replacing one triangle by three smaller triangles when each point is added, and by "flip" operations that replace pairs of triangles by a different pair of triangles.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The history DAG for this algorithm has a vertex for each triangle constructed as part of the algorithm, and edges from each triangle to the two or three other triangles that replace it.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] This structure allows point location queries to be answered efficiently: to find the location of a query point q in the Delaunay triangulation, follow a path in the history DAG, at each step moving to the replacement triangle that contains q.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The final triangle reached in this path must be the Delaunay triangle that contains q.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In a citation graph the vertices are documents with a single publication date.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The edges represent the citations from the bibliography of one document to other necessarily earlier documents.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The classic example comes from the citations between academic papers as pointed out in the 1965 article "Networks of Scientific Papers" by Derek J. de Solla Price who went on to produce the first model of a citation network, the Price model.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In this case the citation count of a paper is just the in-degree of the corresponding vertex of the citation network.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] This is an important measure in citation analysis.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Court judgements provide another example as judges support their conclusions in one case by recalling other earlier decisions made in previous cases.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A final example is provided by patents which must refer to earlier prior art, earlier patents which are relevant to the current patent claim.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] By taking the special properties of directed acyclic graphs into account, one can analyse citation networks with techniques not available when analysing the general graphs considered in many studies using network analysis.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance transitive reduction gives new insights into the citation distributions found in different applications highlighting clear differences in the mechanisms creating citations networks in different contexts.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Another technique is main path analysis, which traces the citation links and suggests the most significant citation chains in a given citation graph.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The Price model is too simple to be a realistic model of a citation network but it is simple enough to allow for analytic solutions for some of its properties.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Many of these can be found by using results derived from the undirected version of the Price model, the Barabási–Albert model.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] However, since Price's model gives a directed acyclic graph, it is a useful model when looking for analytic calculations of properties unique to directed acyclic graphs.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, the length of the longest path, from the n-th node added to the network to the first node in the network, scales as $\ln(n)$ .
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graphs may also be used as a compact representation of a collection of sequences.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In this type of application, one finds a DAG in which the paths form the given sequences.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] When many of the sequences share the same subsequences, these shared subsequences can be represented by a shared part of the DAG, allowing the representation to use less space than it would take to list out all of the sequences separately.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, the directed acyclic word graph is a data structure in computer science formed by a directed acyclic graph with a single source and with edges labeled by letters or symbols; the paths from the source to the sinks in this graph represent a set of strings, such as English words.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Any set of sequences can be represented as paths in a tree, by forming a tree vertex for every prefix of a sequence and making the parent of one of these vertices represent the sequence with one fewer element; the tree formed in this way for a set of strings is called a trie.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Similarly, a binary search tree can be viewed as a rooted DAG where paths represent sorted orderings of keys, though it lacks the path-merging compression found in more complex DAGs.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic word graph saves space over a trie by allowing paths to diverge and rejoin, so that a set of words with the same possible suffixes can be represented by a single tree vertex.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The same idea of using a DAG to represent a family of paths occurs in the binary decision diagram, a DAG-based data structure for representing binary functions.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] In a binary decision diagram, each non-sink vertex is labeled by the name of a binary variable, and each sink and each edge is labeled by a 0 or 1.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] The function value for any truth assignment to the variables is the value at the sink found by following a path, starting from the single source vertex, that at each non-sink vertex follows the outgoing edge labeled with the value of that vertex's variable.
[src:workflow-orchestration/directed-acyclic-graph] Just as directed acyclic word graphs can be viewed as a compressed form of tries, binary decision diagrams can be viewed as compressed forms of decision trees that save space by allowing paths to rejoin when they agree on the results of all remaining decisions.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance specifically refers to a system's capability to handle faults without any degradation or downtime.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] In the event of an error, end-users remain unaware of any issues.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Conversely, a system that experiences errors with some interruption in service or graceful degradation of performance is termed 'resilient'.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] In resilience, the system adapts to the error, maintaining service but acknowledging a certain impact on performance.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Typically, fault tolerance describes computer systems, ensuring the overall system remains functional despite hardware or software issues.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Non-computing examples include structures that retain their integrity despite damage from fatigue, corrosion or impact.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] The first known fault-tolerant computer was SAPO, built in 1951 in Czechoslovakia by Antonín Svoboda.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Its basic design was magnetic drums connected via relays, with a voting method of memory error detection (triple modular redundancy).
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Several other machines were developed along this line, mostly for military use.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Computers with a high amount of runtime that would be under heavy use, such as many of the supercomputers used by insurance companies for their probability monitoring.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Most of the development in the so-called LLNM (Long Life, No Maintenance) computing was done by NASA during the 1960s, in preparation for Project Apollo and other research aspects.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] NASA's first machine went into a space observatory, and their second attempt, the JSTAR computer, was used in Voyager.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] This computer had a backup of memory arrays to use memory recovery methods and thus it was called the Jet Propulsion Laboratory Self-Testing-And-Repairing computer.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] It could detect its own errors and fix them or use redundant modules as needed.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] The computer is still working, as of early 2022.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Hyper-dependable computers were pioneered mostly by aircraft manufacturers, nuclear power companies, and the railroad industry in the United States.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] These entities needed computers with massive amounts of uptime that would fail gracefully enough during a fault to allow continued operation, while relying on constant human monitoring of computer output to detect faults.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] IBM developed the first computer of this kind for NASA for guidance of Saturn V rockets.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Later, BNSF, Unisys, and General Electric built their own.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] In the 1970s, much work happened in the field.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] For instance, F14 CADC had built-in self-test and redundancy.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] In general, the early efforts at fault-tolerant designs were focused mainly on internal diagnosis, where a fault would indicate something was failing and a worker could replace it.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] SAPO, for instance, had a method by which faulty memory drums would emit a noise before failure.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Later efforts showed that to be fully effective, the system had to be self-repairing and diagnosing – isolating a fault and then implementing a redundant backup while alerting a need for repair.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] This is known as N-model redundancy, where faults cause automatic fail-safes and a warning to the operator, and it is still the most common form of level one fault-tolerant design in use today.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Voting was another initial method, as discussed above, with multiple redundant backups operating constantly and checking each other's results.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] For example, if four components reported an answer of 5 and one component reported an answer of 6, the other four would "vote" that the fifth component was faulty and have it taken out of service.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] This is called M out of N majority voting.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Historically, the trend has been to move away from N-model and toward M out of N, as the complexity of systems and the difficulty of ensuring the transitive state from fault-negative to fault-positive did not disrupt operations.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers, in 1976 and Stratus Technologies were among the first companies specializing in the design of fault-tolerant computer systems for online transaction processing.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Hardware fault tolerance sometimes requires that broken parts be removed and replaced with new parts while the system is still operational (in computing known as *hot swapping*).
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Such a system implemented with a single backup is known as **single point tolerant** and represents the vast majority of fault-tolerant systems.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] In such systems the mean time between failures should be long enough for the operators to have sufficient time to fix the broken devices (mean time to repair) before the backup also fails.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] It is helpful if the time between failures is as long as possible, but this is not specifically required in a fault-tolerant system.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance is notably successful in computer applications.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers built their entire business on such machines, which used single-point tolerance to create their NonStop systems with uptimes measured in years.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Fail-safe architectures may encompass also the computer software, for example by process replication.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Data formats may also be designed to degrade gracefully.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Hyper Text Markup Language (HTML) for example, is designed to be forward compatible, allowing Web browsers to ignore new and unsupported HTML entities without causing the document to be unusable.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Additionally, proper user interface design mandates that websites provide an optional lightweight front end that does not rely on JavaScript and has a minimal layout, to ensure wide accessibility and outreach.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] A highly fault-tolerant system might continue at the same level of performance even though one or more components have failed.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] For example, a building with a backup electrical generator will provide the same voltage to wall outlets even if the grid power fails.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] A system that is designed to fail safe, or fail-secure, or **fail gracefully**, whether it functions at a reduced level or fails completely, does so in a way that protects people, property, or data from injury, damage, intrusion, or disclosure.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] In computers, a program might fail-safe by executing a graceful exit (as opposed to an uncontrolled crash) to prevent data corruption after an error occurs.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] A similar distinction is made between "failing well" and "failing badly".
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] A system designed to experience **graceful degradation**, or to **fail soft** (used in computing, similar to "fail safe") operates at a reduced level of performance after some component fails.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] For example, if grid power fails, a building may operate lighting at reduced levels or elevators at reduced speeds.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] In computing, if insufficient network bandwidth is available to stream an online video, a lower-resolution version might be streamed in place of the high-resolution version.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Progressive enhancement is another example, where web pages are available in a basic functional format for older, small-screen, or limited-capability web browsers, but in an enhanced version for browsers capable of handling additional technologies or that have a larger display.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] In fault-tolerant computer systems, programs that are considered robust are designed to continue operation despite an error, exception, or invalid input, instead of failing completely.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Software brittleness is the opposite of robustness.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Resilient networks continue to transmit data despite the failure of some links or nodes.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Resilient buildings and infrastructure are likewise expected to prevent complete failure in situations like earthquakes, floods, or collisions.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] A system with high failure transparency will alert users that a component failure has occurred, even if it continues to operate with full performance, so that failure can be repaired or imminent complete failure anticipated.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Likewise, a fail-fast component is designed to report at the first point of failure, rather than generating reports when downstream components fail.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] This allows easier diagnosis of the underlying problem, and may prevent improper operation in a broken state.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] A **single fault condition** is a situation where one means for protection against a hazard is defective.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] If a single fault condition results unavoidably in another single fault condition, the two failures are considered one single fault condition.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Providing fault-tolerant design for every component is normally not an option.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Associated redundancy brings a number of penalties: increase in weight, size, power consumption, cost, as well as time to design, verify, and test.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] An example of a component that passes all the tests is a car's occupant restraint system.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] While the *primary* occupant restraint system is not normally thought of, it is gravity.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] If the vehicle rolls over or undergoes severe g-forces, then this primary method of occupant restraint may fail.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Restraining the occupants during such an accident is absolutely critical to safety, so the first test is passed.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Accidents causing occupant ejection were quite common before seat belts, so the second test is passed.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] The cost of a redundant restraint method like seat belts is quite low, both economically and in terms of weight and space, so the third test is passed.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Therefore, adding seat belts to all vehicles is an excellent idea.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Other "supplemental restraint systems", such as airbags, are more expensive and so pass that test by a smaller margin.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] It would also be prohibitively costly to further double-up the main components and they would add considerable weight.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] However, the similarly critical systems for actuating the brakes under driver control are inherently less robust, generally using a cable (which can rust, stretch, jam, or snap) or hydraulic fluid (which can leak, boil and develop bubbles, or absorb water and thus lose effectiveness).
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] The cumulatively unlikely combination of total foot brake failure with the need for harsh braking in an emergency will likely result in a collision, but still one at lower speed than would otherwise have been the case.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] In comparison with the foot pedal activated service brake, the parking brake itself is a less critical item, and unless it is being used as a one-time backup for the footbrake, will not cause immediate danger if it is found to be nonfunctional at the moment of application.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, on shallow gradients, the transmission can be shifted into Park, Reverse or First gear, and the transmission lock / engine compression used to hold it stationary, as there is no need for them to include the sophistication to first bring the vehicle to a halt.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] On motorcycles, a similar level of fail-safety is provided by simpler methods; first, the front and rear brake systems are entirely separate, regardless of their method of activation (that can be cable, rod or hydraulic), allowing one system to fail entirely while leaving the other unaffected.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Fault isolation to the failing component – When a failure occurs, the system must be able to isolate the failure to the offending component.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] This requires the addition of dedicated failure detection mechanisms that exist only for the purpose of fault isolation.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Recovery from a fault condition requires classifying the fault or failing component.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Faults are commonly categorized by their locality (internal or external to the system), cause (natural or human-made), duration (permanent or transient), and effect on system behavior.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Fault containment to prevent propagation of the failure – Some failure mechanisms can cause a system to fail by propagating the failure to the rest of the system.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] An example of this kind of failure is the "rogue transmitter" that can swamp legitimate communication in a system and cause overall system failure.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Firewalls or other mechanisms that isolate a rogue transmitter or failing component to protect the system are required.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Availability of reversion modes, which is the abandonment of recent changes, usually to software, that bring a system back to reasonably proper behavior and function.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] In addition, fault-tolerant systems are characterized in terms of both planned service outages and unplanned service outages.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] These are usually measured at the application level and not just at a hardware level.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] The figure of merit is called availability and is expressed as a percentage.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] For example, a five nines system would statistically provide 99.999% availability.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Fault-tolerant systems are typically based on the concept of redundancy.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Research into the kinds of tolerances needed for critical systems involves a large amount of interdisciplinary work.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] The more complex the system, the more carefully all possible interactions have to be considered and prepared for.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] All implementations of RAID, redundant array of independent disks, except RAID 0, are examples of a fault-tolerant storage device that uses data redundancy.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] A lockstep fault-tolerant machine uses replicated elements operating in parallel.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] At any time, all the replications of each element should be in the same state.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] The same inputs are provided to each replication, and the same outputs are expected.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] The outputs of the replications are compared using a voting circuit.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] A machine with two replications of each element is termed dual modular redundant (DMR).
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can then only detect a mismatch and recovery relies on other methods.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] A machine with three replications of each element is termed triple modular redundant (TMR).
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can determine which replication is in error when a two-to-one vote is observed.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] In this case, the voting circuit can output the correct result, and discard the erroneous version.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] After this, the internal state of the erroneous replication is assumed to be different from that of the other two, and the voting circuit can switch to a DMR mode.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] This model can be applied to any larger number of replications.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Lockstep fault-tolerant machines are most easily made fully synchronous, with each gate of each replication making the same state transition on the same edge of the clock, and the clocks to the replications being exactly in phase.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] However, it is possible to build lockstep systems without this requirement.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Bringing the replications into synchrony requires making their internal stored states the same.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] They can be started from a fixed initial state, such as the reset state.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, the internal state of one replica can be copied to another replica.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] One variant of DMR is **pair-and-spare**.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Two replicated elements operate in lockstep as a pair, with a voting circuit that detects any mismatch between their operations and outputs a signal indicating that there is an error.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Another pair operates exactly the same way.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] A final circuit selects the output of the pair that does not proclaim that it is in error.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Pair-and-spare requires four replicas rather than the three of TMR, but has been used commercially.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] The approach has performance costs: because the technique rewrites code to insert dynamic checks for address validity, execution time will increase by 80% to 500%.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Recovery shepherding is a lightweight technique to enable software programs to recover from otherwise fatal errors such as null pointer dereference and divide by zero.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Comparing to the failure oblivious computing technique, recovery shepherding works on the compiled program binary directly and does not need to recompile to program.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] It uses the just-in-time binary instrumentation framework Pin.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] It attaches to the application process when an error occurs, repairs the execution, tracks the repair effects as the execution continues, contains the repair effects within the application process, and detaches from the process after all repair effects are flushed from the process state.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] It does not interfere with the normal execution of the program and therefore incurs negligible overhead.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] For 17 of 18 systematically collected real world null-dereference and divide-by-zero errors, a prototype implementation enables the application to continue to execute to provide acceptable output and service to its users on the error-triggering inputs.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] The circuit breaker design pattern is a technique to avoid catastrophic failures in distributed systems.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Redundancy is the provision of functional capabilities that would be unnecessary in a fault-free environment.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] This can consist of backup components that automatically "kick in" if one component fails.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] For example, large cargo trucks can lose a tire without any major consequences.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] They have many tires, and no one tire is critical (with the exception of the front tires, which are used to steer, but generally carry less load, each and in total, than the other four to 16, so are less likely to fail).
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] The idea of incorporating redundancy in order to improve the reliability of a system was pioneered by John von Neumann in the 1950s.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Two kinds of redundancy are possible: space redundancy and time redundancy.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy provides additional components, functions, or data items that are unnecessary for fault-free operation.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy is further classified into hardware, software and information redundancy, depending on the type of redundant resources added to the system.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] In time redundancy the computation or data transmission is repeated and the result is compared to a stored copy of the previous result.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] The current terminology for this kind of testing is referred to as In Service Fault Tolerance Testing or ISFTT for short.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] There is a difference between fault tolerance and systems that rarely have problems.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] For instance, the Western Electric crossbar systems had failure rates of two hours per forty years, and therefore were highly *fault resistant*.
[src:workflow-orchestration/fault-tolerance] But when a fault did occur, they stopped operating completely, and therefore were not *fault tolerant*.
[src:workflow-orchestration/orchestration-computing] In system administration, **orchestration** is the automated configuration, coordination, deployment, and management of computer systems and software.
[src:workflow-orchestration/orchestration-computing] Many tools exist for automating server configuration and management.
[src:workflow-orchestration/orchestration-computing] Orchestration is often discussed in the context of service-oriented architecture, virtualization, provisioning, converged infrastructure, and dynamic data center topics.
[src:workflow-orchestration/orchestration-computing] Orchestration in this sense is about aligning the business request with the applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:workflow-orchestration/orchestration-computing] In the context of cloud computing, the main difference between workflow automation and orchestration is that workflows are processed and completed as processes within a single domain for automation purposes.
[src:workflow-orchestration/orchestration-computing] Orchestration, meanwhile, incorporates workflows and provides a directed action towards larger goals and objectives.
[src:workflow-orchestration/orchestration-computing] In the context of application programming interfaces (APIs), API orchestration refers to the process of integrating multiple APIs into a unified system to streamline workflows and enhance user experience.
[src:workflow-orchestration/orchestration-computing] The approach coordinates the flow of data, the execution sequence, and the dependencies among different APIs to achieve a defined business objective.
[src:workflow-orchestration/orchestration-computing] API orchestration is commonly applied in environments that utilize microservices architectures or legacy systems, where the interaction of several APIs is required to complete a task.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] In computing, a **pipeline**, also known as a **data pipeline**, is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] The elements of a pipeline are often executed in parallel or in time-sliced fashion.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Some amount of buffer storage is often inserted between elements.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Pipelining is a commonly used concept in everyday life.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] For example, in the assembly line of a car factory, each specific task—such as installing the engine, installing the hood, and installing the wheels—is often done by a separate work station.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] The stations carry out their tasks in parallel, each on a different car.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Once a car has had one task performed, it moves to the next station.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Variations in the time needed to complete the tasks can be accommodated by "buffering" (holding one or more cars in a space between the stations) and/or by "stalling" (temporarily halting the upstream stations), until the next station becomes available.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Suppose that assembling one car requires three tasks that take 20, 10, and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Then, if all three tasks were performed by a single station, the factory would output one car every 45 minutes.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] By using a pipeline of three stations, the factory would output the first car in 45 minutes, and then a new one every 20 minutes.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] As this example shows, pipelining does not decrease the latency, that is, the total time for one item to go through the whole system.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] It does however increase the system's throughput, that is, the rate at which new items are processed after the first one.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] In computing, a pipeline or data pipeline is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] If a pipeline consists of idempotent steps, these can be rerun without altering the outcome beyond the initial run.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] This is advantageous in terms of reliability and maintenance.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Since the throughput of a pipeline cannot be better than that of its slowest element, the designer should try to divide the work and resources among the stages so that they all take the same time to complete their tasks.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] In the car assembly example above, if the three tasks took 15 minutes each, instead of 20, 10, and 15 minutes, the latency would still be 45 minutes, but a new car would then be finished every 15 minutes, instead of 20.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Under ideal circumstances, if all processing elements are synchronized and take the same amount of time to process, then each item can be received by each element just as it is released by the previous one, in a single clock cycle.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] That way, the items will flow through the pipeline at a constant speed, like waves in a water channel.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] In such "wave pipelines", no synchronization or buffering is needed between the stages, besides the storage needed for the data items.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] More generally, buffering between the pipeline stages is necessary when the processing times are irregular, or when items may be created or destroyed along the pipeline.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] For example, in a graphics pipeline that processes triangles to be rendered on the screen, an element that checks the visibility of each triangle may discard the triangle if it is invisible, or may output two or more triangular pieces of the element if they are partly hidden.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Buffering is also needed to accommodate irregularities in the rates at which the application feeds items to the first stage and consumes the output of the last one.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] The buffer between two stages may be simply a hardware register with suitable synchronization and signalling logic between the two stages.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] When a stage A stores a data item in the register, it sends a "data available" signal to the next stage B.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Once B has used that data, it responds with a "data received" signal to A.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Stage A halts, waiting for this signal, before storing the next data item into the register.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Stage B halts, waiting for the "data available" signal, if it is ready to process the next item but stage A has not provided it yet.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] If the processing times of an element are variable, the whole pipeline may often have to stop, waiting for that element and all the previous ones to consume the items in their input buffers.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] The frequency of such pipeline stalls can be reduced by providing space for more than one item in the input buffer of that stage.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Such a multiple-item buffer is usually implemented as a first-in, first-out queue.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] The upstream stage may still have to be halted when the queue gets full, but the frequency of those events will decrease as more buffer slots are provided.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Queueing theory can tell the number of buffer slots needed, depending on the variability of the processing times and on the desired performance.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] If some stage takes (or may take) much longer than the others, and cannot be sped up, the designer can provide two or more processing elements to carry out that task in parallel, with a single input buffer and a single output buffer.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] As each element finishes processing its current data item, it delivers it to the common output buffer, and takes the next data item from the common input buffer.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] This concept of "non-linear" or "dynamic" pipeline is exemplified by shops or banks that have two or more cashiers serving clients from a single waiting queue.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] In some applications, the processing of an item Y by a stage A may depend on the results or effect of processing a previous item X by some later stage B of the pipeline.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] In that case, stage A cannot correctly process item Y until item X has cleared stage B.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] This situation occurs very often in instruction pipelines.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] For example, suppose that Y is an arithmetic instruction that reads the contents of a register that was supposed to have been modified by an earlier instruction X.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Let A be the stage that fetches the instruction operands, and B be the stage that writes the result to the specified register.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] If stage A tries to process instruction Y before instruction X reaches stage B, the register may still contain the old value, and the effect of Y would be incorrect.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] In order to handle such conflicts correctly, the pipeline must be provided with extra circuitry or logic that detects them and takes the appropriate action.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Rather than halt while waiting for X to be finished, stage A may guess whether the branch will be taken or not, and fetch the next instruction Y based on that guess.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] If the guess later turns out to be incorrect (hopefully rarely), the system would have to backtrack and resume with the correct choice.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] To be effectively implemented, data pipelines need a CPU scheduling strategy to dispatch work to the available CPU cores, and the usage of data structures on which the pipeline stages will operate on.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] For example, UNIX derivatives may pipeline commands connecting various processes' standard IO, using the pipes implemented by the operating system.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Some operating systems may provide UNIX-like syntax to string several program runs in a pipeline, but implement the latter as simple serial execution, rather than true pipelining—namely, by waiting for each program to finish before starting the next one.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Lower level approaches may rely on the threads provided by the operating system to schedule work on the stages: both thread pool-based implementations or on a one-thread-per-stage are viable, and exist.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Other strategies relying on cooperative multitasking exist, that do not need multiple threads of execution and hence additional CPU cores, such as using a round-robin scheduler with a coroutine-based framework.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] In this context, each stage may be instantiated with its own coroutine, yielding control back to the scheduler after finishing its round task.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] This approach may need careful control over the process' stages to avoid them abuse their time slice.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] A pipelined system typically requires more resources (circuit elements, processing units, computer memory, etc.) than one that executes one batch at a time, because its stages cannot share those resources, and because buffering and additional synchronization logic may be needed between the elements.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Moreover, the transfer of items between separate processing elements may increase the latency, especially for long pipelines.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] The additional complexity cost of pipelining may be considerable if there are dependencies between the processing of different items, especially if a guess-and-backtrack strategy is used to handle them.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Indeed, the cost of implementing that strategy for complex instruction sets has motivated some radical proposals to simplify computer architecture, such as RISC and VLIW.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] Compilers also have been burdened with the task of rearranging the machine instructions so as to improve the performance of instruction pipelines.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] In recent years the demands on applications and their underlying hardware have been significant.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] For example, building pipelines with single node applications that trawl through the data row by row is no longer feasible with the volume and variety of big data.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] However, with the advent of data analytics engines such as Hadoop, or more recently Apache Spark, it's been possible to distribute large datasets across multiple processing nodes, allowing applications to reach heights of efficiency several hundred times greater than was thought possible before.
[src:workflow-orchestration/pipeline-computing] The effect of this today is that even a mid-level PC using distributed processing in this fashion can handle the building and running of big data pipelines.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:workflow-orchestration/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
[src:workflow-orchestration/workflow-management-system] A **workflow management system** (**WfMS** or **WFMS**) provides an infrastructure for the set-up, performance, and monitoring of a defined sequence of tasks arranged as a workflow application.
[src:workflow-orchestration/workflow-management-system] The underlying theoretical basis of workflow management is the mathematical concept of a Petri net.
[src:workflow-orchestration/workflow-management-system] Each of the workflow models has tasks (nodes) and dependencies between the nodes.
[src:workflow-orchestration/workflow-management-system] Tasks are activated when the dependency conditions are fulfilled.
[src:workflow-orchestration/workflow-management-system] WfMS allows the user to define different workflows for different types of jobs or processes.
[src:workflow-orchestration/workflow-management-system] For example, in a manufacturing setting, a design document might be automatically routed from a designer to a technical director to the production engineer.
[src:workflow-orchestration/workflow-management-system] At each stage in the workflow, one individual or group is responsible for a specific task.
[src:workflow-orchestration/workflow-management-system] Once the task is complete, WfMS ensures that the individuals responsible for the next task are notified and receive the data they need to execute their stage of the process.
[src:workflow-orchestration/workflow-management-system] Workflows can also have more complex dependencies; for example, if a document is to be translated into several languages, a translation manager could select the languages and each selection would then be activated as a work order form for a different translator.
[src:workflow-orchestration/workflow-management-system] Only when all the translators have completed their respective tasks would the next task in the process be activated.
[src:workflow-orchestration/workflow-management-system] It is process management from the top level to the lower level.
[src:workflow-orchestration/workflow-management-system] WfMS also automates redundant tasks and ensures that uncompleted tasks are followed up.
[src:workflow-orchestration/workflow-management-system] A key standard that deals with human tasks in workflows is the WS-BPEL4People Standard by the OASIS Standards Body.
[src:workflow-orchestration/workflow-management-system] WfMS may control automated processes in addition to replacing paperwork order transfers.
